    "reasoning": "The requirement is to implement a 100-bit left/right rotator with synchronous load and enable controls based on the input specification.\n\n1.  **Interface Definition**: The module `TopModule` must match the provided interface: `clk` (input), `load` (input), `ena[1:0]` (input), `data[99:0]` (input), and `q[99:0]` (output).\n2.  **Data Storage**: A 100-bit register (`q_reg`) is needed to hold the current state of the rotator, which will drive the output `q`.\n3.  **Sequential Logic (Clocked Update)**: The core logic must be synchronous (triggered by `posedge clk`). We need an `always @(posedge clk)` block.\n    *   **Load Operation**: If `load` is high, the register `q_reg` must be loaded with `data[99:0]`. (This takes precedence over rotation).\n    *   **Rotation Operation**: If `load` is low, the rotation logic is applied based on `ena[1:0]`:\n        *   `ena == 2'b01` (Rotate Right by 1):\n            The new MSB comes from the old LSB. The new LSB comes from the old second-to-last bit.\n            $q_{new}[99] = q_{old}[98]$, $q_{new}[0] = q_{old}[99]$.\n            Mathematically: $q_{new} = \text{concat}(\text{q}[98:0], q[99])$ (or using shifts: $q \text{ >> } 1 | (q[99] \text{ << } 99)$).\n        *   `ena == 2'b10` (Rotate Left by 1):\n            The new LSB comes from the old MSB. The new MSB comes from the old second-to-last bit.\n            $q_{new}[0] = q_{old}[99]$, $q_{new}[99] = q_{old}[98]$.\n            Mathematically: $q_{new} = \text{concat}(q[98:0], q[99])$ (or using shifts: $q \text{ << } 1 | (q[99] \text{ >> } 99)$).\n        *   `ena == 2'b00` or `ena == 2'b11` (No Change): $q_{new} = q_{old}$.\n4.  **Combinational Logic (Output)**: The output `q` is simply assigned the value of the internal register `q_reg` via an `assign` statement.\n5.  **Initialization**: Since the logic is synchronous and doesn't strictly require a reset, we initialize `q_reg` to 0 using an `initial` block to ensure it starts at a known state.\n\n**Syntax Error Avoidance Advice**:\n*   Ensure bit slicing and concatenation are done correctly. For left rotation by 1 on $Q[99:0]$: $Q_{new} = (Q \text{ << } 1) | (Q[99] \text{ >> } 99)$. This correctly moves $Q[99]$ to $Q_{new}[0]$ and fills the MSB with 0 before ORing the carry-over bit, which needs careful handling for rotation. A cleaner way for rotation is using concatenation: Left rotate: `{Q[98:0], Q[99]}`. Right rotate: `{Q[0], Q[99:1]}`.\n*   The structure requires a single clocked block handling all modes (Load, Rotate Left, Rotate Right, Hold) within the `else` branch when `load` is low.\n",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic load,\n    input  logic [1:0] ena,\n    input  logic [99:0] data,\n    output logic [99:0] q\n);\n\n    // Internal register to hold the state of the rotator\n    logic [99:0] q_reg;\n\n    // Initialize the register to a known state\n    initial begin\n        q_reg = 100'h0;\n    end\n\n    // Combinational assignment for the output\n    assign q = q_reg;\n\n    // Sequential logic block controlled by the clock\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (load) begin\n            // (1) Load operation: Overrides rotation\n            q_reg <= data;\n        end else begin\n            // (2) Rotation operations (Load is inactive)\n            case (ena) \n                2'b01: begin\n                    // (a) Rotate Right by one bit\n                    // New MSB = Old bit 98, New LSB = Old bit 99\n                    // Equivalent to: {q_reg[0], q_reg[99:1]}\n                    q_reg <= {q_reg[0], q_reg[99:1]};\n                end\n                2'b10: begin\n                    // (b) Rotate Left by one bit\n                    // New LSB = Old bit 99, New MSB = Old bit 98\n                    // Equivalent to: {q_reg[98:0], q_reg[99]}\n                    q_reg <= {q_reg[98:0], q_reg[99]};\n                end\n                default: begin\n                    // (c) 2'b00 and 2'b11: No rotation, hold current value\n                    q_reg <= q_reg;\n                end\n            endcase\n        end\n    end\n\nendmodule"
